  What must stay portable vs scoped

  Portable across stack:

   - Strict TypeScript, ESM-only modules, shared domain contracts, no stack traces in API
  responses, audit sensitivity, queue contracts as breaking-change surface, and the need to
  separate confirmed behavior from inferred changes. .github/copilot-instructions.md:13-23,44-71;
  docs/architecture.md:34-49

  Backend-scoped only:

   - Route handler shape, middleware taxonomy, error code/status table, DB transaction
  expectations, and post-write event emission rules. .github/instructions/api.instructions.md:7-50

  Frontend-scoped only:

   - Page/component/client placement, no framework, CSS location, keyboard accessibility, labels,
  semantic HTML. .github/instructions/frontend.instructions.md:7-28

  Implementation sequence

   - Normalize backend contract first: decide whether generic PUT /preferences remains; if yes,
  make it owner-only/read-only consistent with channel routes.
   - Extract notification-preference validation into a pure backend rule surface, with route
  delegating to rule/service instead of embedding authorization/business checks.
   - Move write orchestration into a service that performs audit-first, fail-closed persistence
  with repository calls and any required transaction boundaries.
   - Standardize backend errors to scoped instruction shape/statuses, including machine-readable
  code.
   - Add or update client methods for both single-preference and bulk channel operations, and
  align frontend types with backend enums.
   - Rework the preferences page/component to surface read-only states, bulk channel toggles,
  clearer error feedback, and accessible labeling/grouping.
   - Update API Explorer so examples use valid notification events and expose all supported
  preference endpoints.
   - Add tests last across rule, route, queue/fallback, client, and page/component behavior.

  Validation plan

   - Backend unit tests for permission matrix, delegated-session write blocking, owner-only
  enforcement, event/channel validation, and any California/SMS compliance rule once defined.
   - Backend integration tests for all notification preference endpoints, including 401/403/400
  paths and audit-before-persistence behavior.
   - Queue/notification tests for SMS fallback remaining runtime-only and not mutating stored
  preferences. src/backend/src/queue/handlers/notification-handler.ts:62-76
   - Frontend Vitest tests for client error parsing, preferences page rendering, toggle
  rollback/disabled states, and accessibility checks around labels/keyboard use.
   - Manual regression via Preferences page and API Explorer after the Explorer is corrected.

